value.value: A rare developmental defect of the eye characterized by usually bilateral absence of the normal protrusion of the cornea from the sclera, the corneal curvature being the same as that of the adjacent sclera. Most patients develop hyperopia, hazy corneal limbus, and arcus lipoides at an early age. The condition may present as an autosomal dominant or an autosomal recessive form, with the latter showing more severe signs and symptoms (such as a round and opaque thickening located centrally in the cornea) and more frequent association with other ocular anomalies.
A pigmentation disease characterized by reticulate hyper- and hypo-pigmentated macules in a generalized distribution.

label.value: syndrome caused by partial chromosomal deletion

value.value: A chromosomal disorder consisting of the absence of a part of a chromosome.

label.value: syndrome caused by partial chromosomal duplication

value.value: A chromosomal disorder consisting of the presence of a part of a chromosome in more copies than in a regular genome.
Any corneal dystrophy (disease) in which the cause of the disease is a mutation in the TGFBI gene.
A corneal dystrophy (disease) that involves the corneal epithelium.
A respiratory system disease with a basis in a pathological type I hypersensitivity reaction.
An autoimmune form of peripheral neuropathy.
A allergic disease that involves the digestive tract.
A disease involving the vertebral column.
A rare neural tube defect during pregnancy, resulting in the absence of a large portion of the brain and skull in the fetus.

A disorder characterized by malformations in the structure of the capillaries in the brain. It is caused by mutations in the CCM2, KRIT1 and PDCD10 genes. The capillaries fill with blood and stretch, thereby creating cavernous spaces. Some patients experience headaches, seizures, or visual and hearing disturbances. Cerebral hemorrhage may also occur.
Infections with bacteria of the genus salmonella.
The formation of a blood clot in the lumen of a vessel or heart chamber; causes include coagulation disorders and vascular endothelial injury.
A bone disease that results in formation or resorption abnormalities located in bone.

definition.value: A disease that has its basis in the disruption of bone resorption. Bone resorption is a process in which specialized cells known as osteoclasts degrade the organic and inorganic portions of bone, and endocytose and transport the degradation products.

value.value: OBSOLETE. Any abnormality, anatomical or biochemical, evident at birth or during the neonatal period.

A genetic, non-inheritable disorder caused by osteoblastic differentiation defects that result in the replacement of bone marrow and trabecular bone by fibrous stroma and immature bone. It usually affects a single bone and less frequently multiple bones. Skull, femur, tibia, and humerus are the most frequently affected bones. It manifests with pain, deformities, and fractures.

label.value: myopathy, lactic acidosis, and sideroblastic anemia

value.value: Mitochondrial myopathy and sideroblastic anemia belongs to the heterogeneous family of metabolic myopathies. It is characterized by progressive exercise intolerance manifesting in childhood, onset of sideroblastic anemia around adolescence, lactic acidaemia, and mitochondrial myopathy.
An acute lymphoblastic leukemia occurring during childhood. The majority of cases are B-acute lymphoblastic leukemias. Approximately 15% of the cases are T-acute lymphoblastic leukemias.
A lymphoma composed of immature small to medium-sized precursor lymphoid cells (lymphoblasts). It includes the B- and T-cell lymphoblastic lymphoma.
Candidiasis of the skin manifested as eczema-like lesions of the interdigital spaces, perleche, or chronic paronychia. (Dorland, 27th ed)

label.value: obsolete myeloid neoplasms associated with PDGFRB rearrangement

value.value: A congenital birth syndrome that arises from materal Zika infection.

A rare, invasive colon adenocarcinoma characterized by the presence of sheets of malignant epithelial cells with vesicular nuclei, prominent nucleoli, and abundant eosinophilic cytoplasm. It usually has a favorable prognosis.

A bronchiolo-alveolar adenocarcinoma that is characterized by a tumor cells containing abundant mucin in their cytoplasm and composed of tall columnar cells growing along alveolar walls without stromal invasion.

label.value: agenesis of the corpus callosum with peripheral neuropathy

value.value: Corpus callosum agenesis-neuropathy is a neurodegenerative disorder characterized by severe progressive sensorimotor neuropathy beginning in infancy with resulting hypotonia, areflexia, amyotrophy and variable degrees of dysgenesis of the corpus callosum. Additional features include mild-to-severe intellectual and developmental delays, and psychiatric manifestations that include paranoid delusions, depression, hallucinations, and "autistic-like" features. Affected individuals are usually wheelchair restricted in the second decade of life and die in the third decade of life. The disease is inherited as an autosomal recessive trait.
Myoclonus-dystonia syndrome (MDS) is a rare movement disorder characterized by mild to moderate dystonia along with 'lightning-like' myoclonic jerks.

label.value: complex cortical dysplasia with other brain malformations
cerebral arteriopathy, autosomal dominant, with subcortical infarcts and leukoencephalopathy, type 1

value.value: A CADASIL characterized by migraine, strokes, and white matter lesions that has material basis in heterozygous mutation in the NOTCH3 gene on chromosome 19p13.
An infectious disease involving a pathogenic inflammatory response in the intestinal mucosa.
A primary or metastatic malignant neoplasm involving the ampulla of Vater.
A primary or metastatic malignant neoplasm that affects the duodenum. Representative examples include carcinoma, lymphoma, and sarcoma.
A benign or malignant neoplasm involving the ampulla of Vater.

Pathologic accumulation of air in the interstitium of the lungs, which is caused by the rupture of alveoli and terminal bronchioles, and is most often seen in premature infants that need mechanical ventilation for respiratory distress syndrome.
Disease that disrupts the process by which the vertebrate eye changes optical power to maintain a clear image or focus on an object as its distance varies.
A melanoma that arises from the upper or lower eyelid.
A non-neoplastic or neoplastic disorder that affects the endometrium. Representative examples include endometritis, endometrial hyperplasia, and endometrial carcinoma.
A benign smooth muscle neoplasm arising from the larynx. It is characterized by the presence of spindle cells with cigar-shaped nuclei, interlacing fascicles, and a whorled pattern.

A benign exophytic neoplasm that arises from the larynx, usually the true vocal cords. It is related to human papillomavirus infection and may arise as a single or multiple lesions. It is characterized by the presence of a connective tissue core covered by stratified squamous epithelium. Hoarseness is the presenting symptom. Transformation to carcinoma is rare.
An infectious meningitis caused by infection with Treponema.
An encephalitis caused by infection with Treponema.
